doc.ContractDescription: THE BEHAVIORAL HEALTH OF THE CREW DURING A MISSION TO MARS MISSION COULD BE CHALLENGED DUE TO THE CONDITIONS REQUIRED BY THE FLIGHT. HOWEVER THERE IS NO STANDARDIZED METHOD TO DETECT AND QUANTIFY THE MAGNITUDE OF THE RISK OR ITS LIKELIHOOD. THE OVERARCHING GOAL OF THIS PROJECT IS TO BUILD ON A SUCCESSFUL RECORD OF UNOBTRUSIVE, SOFTWARE-BASED MEASUREMENT OF BEHAVIORAL HEALTH INDICATORS EG MOOD, COGNITIVE FUNCTION, PHYSICAL AND MENTAL FATIGUE, SLEEP QUALITY TO DEVELOP AN INTEGRATED STANDARDIZED SUITE OF BEHAVIORAL HEALTH MEASUREMENT TOOLS THAT WOULD BE QUITE FEASIBLE TO IMPLEMENT WITHIN THE CONSTRAINTS OF SPACEFLIGHT RESEARCH, GROUND-BASED ANALOGS BOTH SHORT AND LONG DURATION, AND PROLONGED MISSIONS IN ISOLATED, CONFINED, EXTREME ENVIRONMENTS LASTING UP TO 12 MONTHS OR LONGER. ACHIEVEMENT OF THIS GOAL WOULD PERMIT A MORE RAPID AND RELIABLE ASSESSMENT AND QUANTIFICATION OF THE RISK OF ADVERSE BEHAVIORAL CONDITIONS PSYCHIATRIC OUTCOMES FOR EXPLORATION CLASS MISSIONS. THE SUITE OF BEHAVIORAL MEDICINE MEASURES WE ARE DEVELOPING WILL BE INTEGRATED ON APPLE IPAD PLATFORM FOR THEIR STANDARDIZED USE IN GROUND ANALOGS RELEVANT TO THE SPACEFLIGHT CONTEXT IE STANDARDIZED BEHAVIORAL MEASURES TOOL OR SBMT. IT WILL INCLUDE THE COGNITION BATTERY, VISUAL ANALOG SCALES VAS OF PERCEIVED MENTAL AND PHYSICAL EXHAUSTION, FATIGUE, STRESS, WORKLOAD, CONFLICT AND SLEEP QUALITY, ACTIGRAPHY FOR MONITORING SLEEP WAKE ACTIVITY, AN AUDIO JOURNAL, THE SPACE DOCK TASK AS AN OPERATIONAL PERFORMANCE MEASURE, AND ADDITIONAL NON-INVASIVE MEASURES RELEVANT TO BEHAVIORAL MEDICINE INFORMED BY A COMPREHENSIVE LITERATURE REVIEW. THE SBMT WILL BE EVALUATED FOR INCLUSION OF THE TASK OF TAKING THE INFORMATION ON MEASUREMENT FEASIBILITY, FLEXIBILITY AND ACCEPTABILITY DURING POST MISSION ASSESSMENTS IN THE PARTICIPANTS STUDIED IN HERA, HI SEAS AND ON ISS. IT WILL BE IMPROVED AS NEEDED, AND AN OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES DOCUMENT WILL BE DEVELOPED TO MAKE IT USE CONVENIENT AND UNOBTRUSIVE FOR DETECTING THE INCIDENT RATE OF BEHAVIORAL HEALTH RISKS IN SPACE AND ON EARTH.

doc.ContractDescription: WE PROPOSE TO PRODUCE A UNIQUE DATABASE OF PLASMA CONDITIONS FOR A SAMPLE OF 14 SUPERNOVA REMNANTS (SNRS). THE BULK OF THE MATERIAL IN SUPERNOVA REMNANTS IS EJECTA, CIRCUMSTELLAR MATTER, OR INTERSTELLAR PLASMA HEATED BY FAST-MOVING SHOCKS AND EMITTING STRONGLY AT X-RAY WAVELENGTHS. CAREFUL CHARACTERIZATION OF THE PLASMA ABUNDANCES, IONIZATION AGES, AND TEMPERATURES CAN PLACE CONSTRAINTS ON SUPERNOVA AND STELLAR EVOLUTION MODELS. WE WILL USE ARCHIVAL X-RAY OBSERVATIONS OF A WIDE VARIETY OF SNRS TO PRODUCE DISTRIBUTIONS OF TEMPERATURE, IONIZATION STATE, AND ABUNDANCES OF PLASMA THROUGHOUT THE ENTIRE VOLUME OF EACH SNR, AND WILL COMPARE THESE OBSERVATIONAL DISTRIBUTIONS TO THOSE PREDICTED BY NUMERICAL MODELS OF SUPERNOVA EXPLOSIONS AND REMNANT EVOLUTION. WE WILL ACCOMPLISH THIS BY APPLYING A NEW TECHNIQUE, SMOOTHED PARTICLE INFERENCE (SPI), TO THE XMM-NEWTON OBSERVATIONS OF 12 GALACTIC AND 2 LARGE MAGELLANIC CLOUD SNRS. SPI IS A BAYESIAN MODELING PROCESS THAT FITS A POPULATION OF GAS BLOBS ("SMOOTHED PARTICLES") SUCH THAT THEIR SUPERPOSED EMISSION REPRODUCES THE OBSERVED SPATIAL AND SPECTRAL DISTRIBUTION OF PHOTONS. EMISSION- WEIGHTED DISTRIBUTIONS OF PLASMA PROPERTIES ARE THEN EXTRACTED FROM THE PROPERTIES OF THE INDIVIDUAL BLOBS. THIS TECHNIQUE HAS IMPORTANT ADVANTAGES OVER THE ANALYSIS TECHNIQUES APPLIED IN THE PAST, WHICH IMPLICITLY ASSUMED THAT REMNANTS ARE TWO-DIMENSIONAL OBJECTS IN WHICH EACH LINE OF SIGHT ENCOMPASSES A SINGLE PLASMA, PERHAPS CHARACTERIZED BY TWO TEMPERATURE COMPONENTS. BY CONTRAST, SPI ALLOWS SUPERPOSITION OF AS MANY BLOBS OF PLASMA AS ARE NEEDED TO MATCH THE SPECTRUM OBSERVED IN EACH DIRECTION, WITHOUT THE NEED TO BIN THE DATA SPATIALLY. WE PRESENT PRELIMINARY RESULTS FROM AN SPI ANALYSIS OF W49B TO SHOWCASE THE RESULTS THAT CAN BE ACHIEVED WITH THIS TECHNIQUE. IN ADDITION TO PROVIDING DEEPER INSIGHT INTO THE CONDITIONS OF INDIVIDUAL REMNANTS AND THEIR RELATION TO THE SURROUNDING MEDIUM AND PROGENITOR STARS, APPLICATION OF SPI TO A LARGER SAMPLE OF SNRS ALLOWS FOR CONSISTENT COMPARISONS OF PLASMA CONDITIONS BETWEEN REMNANTS. THE SUPERNOVA REMNANTS IN THE PROPOSED SAMPLE INCLUDE BOTH CORE-COLLAPSE AND TYPE IA, AND COVER A WIDE RANGE OF AGES AND ENVIRONMENTS. THIS WILL ENABLE US TO INVESTIGATE RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN ABUNDANCE, TEMPERATURE, AND IONIZATION AGE DISTRIBUTIONS AND SNR TYPE, ENVIRONMENT, AND AGE, ULTIMATELY PROVIDING A MORE COMPLETE UNDERSTANDING OF SUPERNOVA REMNANTS AS A CLASS.

doc.ContractDescription: FROM FLICKER TO JITTER: PREDICTING STELLAR RADIAL VELOCITY VARIATIONS FROM PHOTOMETRIC VARIABILITY. GIVEN THAT MOST EXTRASOLAR PLANETS ARE DETECTED BY THEIR INFLUENCE ON THEIR HOST STAR, THE HUNT FOR THESE OBJECTS IS LIMITED BY PROCESSES OCCURRING ON THE SURFACES OF THESE STARS STELLAR "NOISE" WHICH CAN SWAMP OR MIMIC PLANETARY SIGNALS. THIS IS PARTICULARLY SO IN THE RADIAL VELOCITY (RV) DOMAIN, WHERE THIS "NOISE" IS TERMED "JITTER." ADDED TO THIS, PHOTOMETRIC EXTRASOLAR PLANET SURVEYS, SUCH AS K2 AND TESS, WILL UNCOVER THOUSANDS OF TRANSITING PLANETS IN ADDITION TO THOSE FOUND BY KEPLER WHICH ARE ALREADY SEVERELY TAXING GROUNDBASED FOLLOW-UP RV RESOURCES: ONLY ~5% OF ALL PLANETARY CANDIDATES DISCOVERED BY KEPLER HAVE THUS FAR HAVE BEEN CONFIRMED BY RVS. IT IS THEREFORE IMPERATIVE TO DEVISE A SIMPLE WAY TO PRIORITIZE FUTURE FOLLOW-UP CAMPAIGNS, BY ENABLING PLANET HUNTERS TO PREDICT IN ADVANCE WHICH STARS WILL EXHIBIT THE LEAST RV NOISE. THE GOAL OF THIS PROPOSAL IS TO USE ULTRA-HIGH PRECISION, LONG TIME-BASELINE LIGHT CURVES FROM NASA'S RE-PURPOSED KEPLER MISSION (K2) TOGETHER WITH RV JITTER MEASUREMENTS OBTAINED BY THE CALIFORNIA PLANET SEARCH (CPS) TO (1) DEVELOP AN EMPIRICAL PREDICTOR OF RV JITTER FROM LIGHT CURVES AND (2) EXAMINE THE AGE, ACTIVITY, AND SPECTRAL TYPE DEPENDENCE OF THESE RV JITTER-PHOTOMETRIC VARIABILITY RELATIONS. THE RESULTS OF THIS WORK MAY ULTIMATELY ALLOW US TO FINALLY UNEARTH THE UNDERLYING PHYSICAL CAUSES OF POORLY-UNDERSTOOD RV JITTER. WE PROPOSE TO DEVELOP A WAY TO USE THE PUBLICLY AVAILABLE LIGHT CURVES OBTAINED BY K2 TO ASSESS WHICH OBJECTS ARE MOST SUITABLE FOR RV PLANET SEARCHES. THIS WILL ENABLE RV TEAMS TO RESERVE THEIR TELESCOPE TIME AND RESOURCES ONLY FOR THE MOST INTERESTING AND PROMISING TARGETS RATHER THAN DEPLOYING THEM ON STARS THAT LATER TURN OUT TO BE TOO "JITTERY" FOR DOPPLER SEARCHES. AS SUCH, THIS PROPOSAL DIRECTLY SUPPORTS NASA'S GOAL OF UNDERSTANDING EXOPLANETARY SYSTEMS BY "[AIDING] IN THE DETECTION OF NEW EXOPLANETS." THE PROPOSED WORK WILL HAVE THE ADDED BENEFIT OF ENHANCING OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE PHYSICAL ORIGINS OF JITTER, THEREBY ENABLING US TO DEVISE WAYS TO BYPASS OR REMOVE THE JITTER SIGNAL. THE RESULT: THE REMOVAL OF A FUNDAMENTAL LIMITING FACTOR IN RV PLANET SEARCHES, AND THE OPENING OF NEW RV PLANET SEARCH DOMAINS, SO KEY TO THE FULFILLMENT OF THE NASA SMD OBJECTIVE OF "[DISCOVERING] HOW THE UNIVERSE WORKS, [EXPLORING] HOW IT BEGAN AND EVOLVED, AND [SEARCHING] FOR LIFE ON PLANETS AROUND OTHER STARS." IN PARTICULAR, DETERMINING THE AGE-DEPENDENCE OF RV JITTER-PHOTOMETRIC VARIABILITY RELATIONS HAS THE POTENTIAL TO PERMIT THE RV DETECTION OF PLANETS AROUND YOUNGER, MORE ACTIVE STARS AND HENCE AID IN IMPROVING THE "UNDERSTANDING OF THE ORIGINS OF EXOPLANETARY SYSTEMS," ONE OF THE CORE GOALS OF THE XRP SOLICITATION.
